  "response": "Here's an overview of comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different jurisdictions:\n\n1. United States\n- Comprehensive Bank Secrecy Act\n- Robust reporting requirements\n- Aggressive criminal prosecution\n- Strict federal and state-level regulations\n- Significant financial penalties\n\n2. European Union\n- Unified Anti-Money Laundering Directive\n- Centralized regulatory framework\n- Enhanced customer due diligence\n- Consistent reporting standards\n- Collaborative cross-border enforcement\n\n3. United Kingdom\n- Strict financial transparency laws\n- Advanced technological monitoring\n- Sophisticated risk-based approach\n- Strong international cooperation\n- Comprehensive suspicious transaction reporting\n\n4. Switzerland\n- Historically more permissive banking secrecy\n- Gradual regulatory tightening\n- Enhanced international compliance\n- Sophisticated financial monitoring systems\n\n5. China\n- Centralized regulatory approach\n- Strict government oversight\n- Growing emphasis on financial transparency\n- Significant penalties for non-compliance\n\n6. United Arab Emirates\n- Emerging regulatory framework\n- Increasing international compliance\n- Developing sophisticated monitoring mechanisms\n\nKey comparative observations:\n- Increasing global regulatory convergence\n- Technology-driven detection methods\n- Growing international cooperation\n- Emphasis on preventative mechanisms\n- Risk-based regulatory approaches\n\nNote: This overview provides general comparative insights and is not comprehensive legal guidance.",
